{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Hz4MKNxsVqHkNznvHk33mz","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So the ray-client pod is just `sleep infinity` - it's not starting a local Ray instance. When `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` is called, it tries to start a local raylet in the pod (which should work in theory), but the `node_ip_address.json` file is not being written.\n\nLet me check if there are any issues with the local raylet startup. The problem might be that:\n1. The raylet binary can't start (permission issue, missing libraries, etc.)\n2. The raylet needs specific ports to be free\n\nLet me try to manually run `ray start --address=ray-head:6379` in the ray-client pod to see what happens.\nActually, in Ray 2.x with a GCS address, the connection behavior is different. When I pass a non-ray:// address like that, it attempts to connect to the GCS and register as a new node, starting a local raylet to handle the actual work. Let me test whether `ray start` even works in the pod.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1711,"cache_read_input_tokens":33759,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1711},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f9df3909-7b52-4932-ac00-609e9b5a8b01","uuid":"59322ce0-2153-408c-b166-d7c1691c92ff","request_id":"req_011CcekBdzcXgD61b4GQ4Ved"}
